                    "Json": {
                      "exit_status": "0",
                      "stdout": "3348: .TP\n3349: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-position\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3350: The position of the \\(lqquick\\(rq terminal window.\n3351: To learn more about the quick terminal, see the documentation for the\n3352: \\f[CR]toggle_quick_terminal\\f[R] binding action.\n3353: .RS\n3354: .PP\n3355: Valid values are:\n3356: .IP \\(bu 2\n3357: \\f[CR]top\\f[R] \\- Terminal appears at the top of the screen.\n3358: .IP \\(bu 2\n3359: \\f[CR]bottom\\f[R] \\- Terminal appears at the bottom of the screen.\n3360: .IP \\(bu 2\n3361: \\f[CR]left\\f[R] \\- Terminal appears at the left of the screen.\n3362: .IP \\(bu 2\n3363: \\f[CR]right\\f[R] \\- Terminal appears at the right of the screen.\n3364: .IP \\(bu 2\n3365: \\f[CR]center\\f[R] \\- Terminal appears at the center of the screen.\n3366: .PP\n3367: On macOS, changing this configuration requires restarting Ghostty\n3368: completely.\n---\n3374: .TP\n3375: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-size\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3376: The size of the quick terminal.\n3377: .RS\n3378: .PP\n3379: The size can be specified either as a percentage of the screen\n3380: dimensions (height/width), or as an absolute size in pixels.\n3381: Percentage values are suffixed with \\f[CR]%\\f[R] (e.g.\\ \\f[CR]20%\\f[R])\n3382: while pixel values are suffixed with \\f[CR]px\\f[R]\n3383: (e.g.\\ \\f[CR]300px\\f[R]).\n3384: A bare value without a suffix is a config error.\n3385: .PP\n3386: When only one size is specified, the size parameter affects the size of\n3387: the quick terminal on its \\f[I]primary axis\\f[R], which depends on its\n3388: position: height for quick terminals placed on the top or bottom, and\n3389: width for left or right.\n3390: The primary axis of a centered quick terminal depends on the\n3391: monitor\\(cqs orientation: height when on a landscape monitor, and width\n3392: when on a portrait monitor.\n3393: .PP\n3394: The \\f[I]secondary axis\\f[R] would be maximized for non\\-center\n---\n3403: .TP\n3404: \\f[B]\\f[CB]gtk\\-quick\\-terminal\\-layer\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3405: The layer of the quick terminal window.\n3406: The higher the layer, the more windows the quick terminal may conceal.\n3407: .RS\n3408: .PP\n3409: Valid values are:\n3410: .IP \\(bu 2\n3411: \\f[CR]overlay\\f[R]\n3412: .RS 2\n3413: .PP\n3414: The quick terminal appears in front of all windows.\n3415: .RE\n3416: .IP \\(bu 2\n3417: \\f[CR]top\\f[R] (default)\n3418: .RS 2\n3419: .PP\n3420: The quick terminal appears in front of normal windows but behind\n3421: fullscreen overlays like lock screens.\n3422: .RE\n3423: .IP \\(bu 2\n---\n3441: .TP\n3442: \\f[B]\\f[CB]gtk\\-quick\\-terminal\\-namespace\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3443: The namespace for the quick terminal window.\n3444: .RS\n3445: .PP\n3446: This is an identifier that is used by the Wayland compositor and/or\n3447: scripts to determine the type of layer surfaces and to possibly apply\n3448: unique effects.\n3449: .PP\n3450: GTK Wayland only.\n3451: .PP\n3452: Available since: 1.2.0\n3453: .RE\n3454: .TP\n3455: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-screen\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3456: The screen where the quick terminal should show up.\n3457: .RS\n3458: .PP\n3459: Valid values are:\n3460: .IP \\(bu 2\n3461: \\f[CR]main\\f[R] \\- The screen that the operating system recommends as\n---\n3454: .TP\n3455: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-screen\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3456: The screen where the quick terminal should show up.\n3457: .RS\n3458: .PP\n3459: Valid values are:\n3460: .IP \\(bu 2\n3461: \\f[CR]main\\f[R] \\- The screen that the operating system recommends as\n3462: the main screen.\n3463: On macOS, this is the screen that is currently receiving keyboard input.\n3464: This screen is defined by the operating system and not chosen by\n3465: Ghostty.\n3466: .IP \\(bu 2\n3467: \\f[CR]mouse\\f[R] \\- The screen that the mouse is currently hovered over.\n3468: .IP \\(bu 2\n3469: \\f[CR]macos\\-menu\\-bar\\f[R] \\- The screen that contains the macOS menu\n3470: bar as set in the display settings on macOS.\n3471: This is a bit confusing because every screen on macOS has a menu bar,\n3472: but this is the screen that contains the primary menu bar.\n3473: .PP\n3474: The default value is \\f[CR]main\\f[R] because this is the recommended\n---\n3479: .TP\n3480: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-animation\\-duration\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3481: Duration (in seconds) of the quick terminal enter and exit animation.\n3482: Set it to 0 to disable animation completely.\n3483: This can be changed at runtime.\n3484: .RS\n3485: .PP\n3486: Only implemented on macOS.\n3487: .RE\n3488: .TP\n3489: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-autohide\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3490: Automatically hide the quick terminal when focus shifts to another\n3491: window.\n3492: Set it to false for the quick terminal to remain open even when it loses\n3493: focus.\n3494: .RS\n3495: .PP\n3496: Defaults to true on macOS and on false on Linux/BSD.\n3497: This is because global shortcuts on Linux require system configuration\n3498: and are considerably less accessible than on macOS, meaning that it is\n3499: more preferable to keep the quick terminal open until the user has\n---\n3488: .TP\n3489: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-autohide\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3490: Automatically hide the quick terminal when focus shifts to another\n3491: window.\n3492: Set it to false for the quick terminal to remain open even when it loses\n3493: focus.\n3494: .RS\n3495: .PP\n3496: Defaults to true on macOS and on false on Linux/BSD.\n3497: This is because global shortcuts on Linux require system configuration\n3498: and are considerably less accessible than on macOS, meaning that it is\n3499: more preferable to keep the quick terminal open until the user has\n3500: completed their task.\n3501: This default may change in the future.\n3502: .RE\n3503: .TP\n3504: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-space\\-behavior\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3505: This configuration option determines the behavior of the quick terminal\n3506: when switching between macOS spaces.\n3507: macOS spaces are virtual desktops that can be manually created or are\n3508: automatically created when an application is in full\\-screen mode.\n---\n3503: .TP\n3504: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-space\\-behavior\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3505: This configuration option determines the behavior of the quick terminal\n3506: when switching between macOS spaces.\n3507: macOS spaces are virtual desktops that can be manually created or are\n3508: automatically created when an application is in full\\-screen mode.\n3509: .RS\n3510: .PP\n3511: Valid values are:\n3512: .IP \\(bu 2\n3513: \\f[CR]move\\f[R] \\- When switching to another space, the quick terminal\n3514: will also moved to the current space.\n3515: .IP \\(bu 2\n3516: \\f[CR]remain\\f[R] \\- The quick terminal will stay only in the space\n3517: where it was originally opened and will not follow when switching to\n3518: another space.\n3519: .PP\n3520: The default value is \\f[CR]move\\f[R].\n3521: .PP\n3522: Only implemented on macOS.\n3523: On Linux the behavior is always equivalent to \\f[CR]move\\f[R].\n---\n3527: .TP\n3528: \\f[B]\\f[CB]quick\\-terminal\\-keyboard\\-interactivity\\f[B]\\f[R]\n3529: Determines under which circumstances that the quick terminal should\n3530: receive keyboard input.\n3531: See the corresponding \\c\n3532: .UR https://wayland.app/protocols/wlr-layer-shell-unstable-v1#zwlr_layer_surface_v1:enum:keyboard_interactivity\n3533: Wayland documentation\n3534: .UE \\c\n3535: \\ for a more detailed explanation of the behavior of each option.\n3536: .RS\n3537: .RS\n3538: .PP\n3539: [!NOTE] The exact behavior of each option may differ significantly\n3540: across compositors \\(en experiment with them on your system to find one\n3541: that suits your liking!\n3542: .RE\n3543: .PP\n3544: Valid values are:\n3545: .IP \\(bu 2\n3546: \\f[CR]none\\f[R]\n3547: .RS 2\n---\n4765: .TP\n4766: \\f[B]\\f[CB]term\\f[B]\\f[R]\n4767: This will be used to set the \\f[CR]TERM\\f[R] environment variable.\n4768: HACK: We set this with an \\f[CR]xterm\\f[R] prefix because vim uses that\n4769: to enable key protocols (specifically this will enable\n4770: \\f[CR]modifyOtherKeys\\f[R]), among other features.\n4771: An option exists in vim to modify this:\n4772: \\f[CR]:set keyprotocol=ghostty:kitty\\f[R], however a bug in the\n4773: implementation prevents it from working properly.\n4774: https://github.com/vim/vim/pull/13211 fixes this.\n4775: .TP\n4776: \\f[B]\\f[CB]enquiry\\-response\\f[B]\\f[R]\n4777: String to send when we receive \\f[CR]ENQ\\f[R] (\\f[CR]0x05\\f[R]) from the\n4778: command that we are running.\n4779: Defaults to an empty string if not set.\n4780: .TP\n4781: \\f[B]\\f[CB]async\\-backend\\f[B]\\f[R]\n4782: Configures the low\\-level API to use for async IO, eventing, etc.\n4783: .RS\n4784: .PP\n4785: Most users should leave this set to \\f[CR]auto\\f[R].\n---\n5446: .TP\n5447: \\f[B]\\f[CB]toggle_quick_terminal\\f[B]\\f[R]\n5448: Toggle the quick terminal.\n5449: .RS\n5450: .PP\n5451: The quick terminal, also known as the \\(lqQuake\\-style\\(rq or drop\\-down\n5452: terminal, is a terminal window that appears on demand from a keybinding,\n5453: often sliding in from a screen edge such as the top.\n5454: This is useful for quick access to a terminal without having to open a\n5455: new window or tab.\n5456: .PP\n5457: The terminal state is preserved between appearances, so showing the\n5458: quick terminal after it was already hidden would display the same window\n5459: instead of creating a new one.\n5460: .PP\n5461: As quick terminals are often useful when other windows are currently\n5462: focused, they are best used with \\f[I]global\\f[R] keybinds.\n5463: For example, one can define the following key bind to toggle the quick\n5464: terminal from anywhere within the system by pressing\n5465: \\f[CR]Cmd+\\(ga\\f[R]:\n5466: .IP\n---\n",
